Black brown glaze (gritty and flaky) on the exterior surface of the sherd. Interior is unglazed. The sherd is stamped with two vertical characters: qing xiang (清香). Qing is only a partial character.

Gritty greenish brown glaze on the jar; partial glaze which covers approximately half of the jar. The lower portion of the jar is unglazed, but bears a purple red slip. There are four broken sections of which the largest (the dimensions of which are recorded in this entry) contains two lugs and 51% of the mouth which is unglazed and the unglazed upper portion extends down to the area above the lugs. The same purple slip is visible and there appears to be a gritty shiny sheen to the mouth and the unglazed upper portion, which probably is the result of self-glazing due to the high firing temperature in the kiln. The mouth rim is rolled. The liquid glaze was likely poured over middle section of the jar and then scraped away (?). The second larger fragment contains a lug, but does not fit the main  part of the jar. Two other smaller fragments.
Blackish brown gritty glaze on the exterior surface of the jar. Two sherds conjoined. Lug is broken and there is a stamp with two Chinese characters: qing xiang (清香).
Necked jarlet with with dark brown glaze down 3/4 of the vessel. Everted rolled rim of the mouth. Partial glaze on the interior just beneath the mouth extending halfway down the jarlet's neck.
